.TH WALK 3 "" "" "Inferno Communications Protocol, Styx"
.PP
.SH NAME
walk \- descend a directory hierarchy
.SH SYNOPSYS
.IP
.EX
Twalk tag [2] fid [2] name [28]
Rwalk tag [2] fid [2] qid [8]
.EE
.PP
.SH DESCRIPTION
The 
.I walk
request looks for the file 
.I name
in the directory represented by 
.I fid
.
.PP
For the 
.I walk
to succeed, the file identified by 
.I fid
must be a directory and the implied user of the request must have permission to search the directory.
(See
.IR 0intro (3)
).
.PP
After a successful 
.I walk
, 
.I fid
represents the specified file.
The 
.I qid
for the new file is returned with the 
.I walk
reply message.
.PP
A 
.I walk
of the name 
.I \[aq].\[aq]
in the root directory of a server is a no\-op.
.PP
.SH ENTRY POINTS
The 
.B chdir
system call causes a 
.I walk
.
.PP
One or more 
.I walk
messages may be generated by any of the following calls, which evaluate file names: 
.B bind
, 
.B create
, 
.B mount
, 
.B open
, 
.B remove
, 
.B stat
, 
.B unmount
, and 
.B wstat
.
.PP
The file name element \[aq].\[aq] (dot, current directory) is interpreted locally and is not transmitted in 
.I walk
messages.
.PP
.SH SEE ALSO
.PP
.TS
tab(@);
l.
